{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612160"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:18:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:18:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16263"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16263"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0.68,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65150"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8954"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16263"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50586"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8405"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21300"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65150"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBody composition undergoes significant changes throughout the human lifespan.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a typical change in body composition that occurs with advancing age?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased skeletal muscle mass","Increased total body water percentage","Increased body fat percentage","Increased bone mineral density","Increased lean tissue mass"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWith advancing age, there is typically an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease in body fat percentage\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs due to reduced physical activity, decreased metabolic rate, and hormonal changes. Fat tends to redistribute, with increased visceral adiposity being particularly common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent changes that typically go in the opposite direction with aging:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased skeletal muscle mass\u003C/strong\u003E - Muscle mass typically decreases with age in a process known as sarcopenia. Sarcopenia is often accompanied by increased fat infiltration into muscle tissue (known as myosteatosis), which reduces muscle quality and function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased total body water percentage\u003C/strong\u003E - Total body water percentage decreases with age, largely due to loss of muscle mass\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased bone mineral density\u003C/strong\u003E - Bone density typically decreases with age, particularly after menopause in women\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased lean tissue mass\u003C/strong\u003E - Lean tissue mass decreases with age as part of normal aging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes in body composition can have important implications for health, including increased risk of metabolic disorders and reduced functional capacity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Body composition changes with age include increased fat mass and decreased lean mass.","Total body water percentage decreases with age due to loss of muscle mass.","Physical activity and muscle mass naturally decline with advancing age."],"references":["Ou MY, Zhang H, Tan PC, Zhou SB, Li QF. Adipose tissue aging: mechanisms and therapeutic implications. Cell Death Dis. 2022 Apr 4;13(4):300. doi: 10.1038/s41419-022-04752-6. PMID: 35379822; PMCID: PMC8980023.","Ponti F, Santoro A, Mercatelli D, Gasperini C, Conte M, Martucci M, Sangiorgi L, Franceschi C, Bazzocchi A. Aging and Imaging Assessment of Body Composition: From Fat to Facts. Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2020 Jan 14;10:861. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2019.00861. PMID: 31993018; PMCID: PMC6970947.","St-Onge MP, Gallagher D. Body composition changes with aging: the cause or the result of alterations in metabolic rate and macronutrient oxidation? Nutrition. 2010 Feb;26(2):152-5. doi: 10.1016/j.nut.2009.07.004. Epub 2009 Dec 8. PMID: 20004080; PMCID: PMC2880224."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50586"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16263"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50586"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T16:32:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T16:33:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8954"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65150"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"htt